  "prompt": "What are ductile materials?",
  "response": "Ductile materials are those that can undergo significant plastic deformation before rupture or failure. This means they can be stretched, bent, or compressed into a new shape without breaking. Ductility is a key property in materials science, particularly for applications that require materials to absorb energy during deforming processes and still maintain their integrity.\n\nCommon examples of ductile materials include:\n- Metals such as gold, silver, copper, aluminum, and steel\n- Certain polymers\n- Some types of glass\n\nThese materials are often used in manufacturing and construction where flexibility and durability are important. Ductility is measured quantitatively in terms of elongation or reduction in area during tensile testing.",
